> >My gut reaction is to oppose this on principle.  I favor
> incentives to Vote
> >over penalties for not Voting.  I'm not opposed to a tax but using it to
> >penalize savings I do oppose.
>
> I was hoping for more than a gut reaction - an argument, say.


Well, I feel that I have a right to play by my gut if I choose.  You may
play in a gutless manner if you so choose!  :)

The reason I didn't give a more thorough argument is that I don't have a
great amount of time to devote to the game.  I thought it better to offer my
opinion rather than nothing at all.  I'm sorry if that's unacceptable to
you.


>I do not
> think it is fair to say that lowering the VTCL means penalizing Players
> for not voting. It is, in fact, exactly what you say you want: an
> incentive to vote, nothing more.


I fail to see how you can say that lowering the VTCL is not a penalty for
not voting.  Especially since that is precisely what you are trying to
accomplish.  You wish to forcibly remove VT's from players that do not vote
simply because they did not vote.  In my book that's a penalty for not
voting.

As to any arguments that this is an incentive to vote, I hope you don't
develop any employee incentive programs where you work unless your goal is
to increase personnel turnover! :)

> If you insist that the operation of the VTCL constitutes a penalty for
> not voting, then you must be opposed to the VTCL tout court. Yet you say
> you are not opposed to a tax, so it's not clear to me exactly what your
> position on the VTCL is.

Absolute nonsense and rubbish.  By this standard I must be opposed to knives
because I am opposed to killing people with knives.  I am not opposed to a
reasonable level of taxation for the purpose of funding the bank so that the
collective debts of the Agoran community can be paid.  (This, btw, is not at
all what is being done with the taxation system we have now, but, perhaps
foolishly,  I have hope.)  Such a use for taxation is bearable precisely
because the rampant inflation that otherwise results is far worse than the
taxation itself.  The lesser of two evils.

>I can't see any difference in basic principle
> between a VTCL set at 9 and one set at 5. The latter value, as I argued,
> simply provides an incentive for Players to spend rather than save.
>

The difference is that a VTCL of 5 does not allow a reasonable level of
savings, imo.  But apparently you don't see this because of your view that
penalizing savings is an incentive to vote.

I happen to feel that a reasonable level of savings can help to make a more
interesting game.  Because of my savings I'm in a much better position to do
battle against you on this proposal.  If I chose I could buy quite a few
AGAINST votes (I'm open to offers).  I think that such a fight makes the
game more interesting.  But if the VTCL is lowered too much it would be a
difficult thing to accomplish.

> >
> >I strongly oppose this.  I intend to vote against it and I
> encourage others
> >to do likewise.
>
> Again, I was hoping to elicit from you cogent reasons for your
> opposition. What is so terrifying about a 3 month experiment with a
> different voting regime? Nomic is, after all, about change. I can't
> emphasize enough that if we don't like this, it will go completely away
> on its own, without anybody's having to do anything.
>

There is nothing terrifying about it short of having to spend my VTs on
proposals that aren't worth the PNotes necessary to get them out of the
queue.  As I have said many times before, I will vote when I see a proposal
that I care strongly enough about that it's worth a VT to me.  This one
definitely qualifies in that regard unlike many recent proposals (I will be
the first to admit that I, myself, haven't offered any interesting proposals
and thus am part of the problem).

I am so much opposed to this, I will offer two VTs the first 4 players to
vote AGAINST this.  Be careful to avoid Public Voting however.

> >Surely there must be a way to provide incentive to Vote?  Must
> an increase
> >in Voting be achieved by penalties?
>
> As I say, lowering the VTCL is one such way. It ought to provide a
> strong incentive to vote, in which case not too many Players will end up
> being penalized by A Duty to Vote.
>

And the thug that beats you for the contents of your wallet provides a
strong incentive to remain indoors at night.  Can't we have some type of
positive incentive?

> I'm open to other ideas.

I must admit that I can't offer much.  Perhaps, a rebate on the Voting
Tariff for those that vote on the 'winning' side?  Perhaps an award given
weekly or monthly to the player that voted the most often?

>I've already taken on board your suggestion of
> increasing VT supply.
>

Yes, I must admit that you have done that.  An increase in VT supply will
hopefully result in more votes.

I'm not against your goal of increasing votes.  I too would like to see more
voting.  I'm just opposed to your methods.  As an unemployed player I cannot
quickly amass wealth to be able to make a big play in the game.  I therefore
invest significant time saving and significant effort looking for the right
play to spend that wealth on.  I don't want that time and effort to be lost
by a sudden reduction of the VTCL.  Not all of us who enjoy playing the game
have the time on a weekly or daily basis to hold an Office.  I know I don't.
I wish that I did.  I'd gladly give that time to the game.  But I don't, and
so the pace at which I play is slower.  Should I be penalized for that?  I
think not.



